				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/08/opinion/08takingnote-jobs-web/08takingnote-jobs-web-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/08/opinion/08takingnote-jobs-web/08takingnote-jobs-web-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/08/opinion/08takingnote-jobs-web/08takingnote-jobs-web-blog480.jpg" id="100000003843429" width="480" height="359" alt="A job fair in Sunrise, Fla."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="359"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A job fair in Sunrise, Fla.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Alan Diaz/Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The <a href="//www.bls.gov/news.release/empsit.nr0.htm">jobs report for July</a>, released on Friday, showed steady if unspectacular job growth. The economy created 215,000 jobs, in line with average job creation so far this year. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The growth in July was centered in retail, restaurants and other low-paying service jobs, though there was also encouraging  growth in higher-paying fields, including construction and finance. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What was lacking â in July, as in every other month in the past several years â was any appreciable growth in wages. Average hourly earnings for all private-sector employees rose by 0.5 cents, to $24.99. Take away the minority of employees who are bosses, and the increase was just 0.3 cents, to $21.01 an hour, or $42,000 a year for a full-time job. <span id="more-20543"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Over all, the average annualized growth rate for wages over the past three months comes to 1.9 percent, barely outpacing inflation. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Job growth without pay raises is a discouraging sign of slack in the job market. For example, the share of the population age 25 to 54 that is working <a href="//www.bls.gov/news.release/empsit.nr0.htm">is stuck</a> at recession-era levels and, worse, has stopped improving in the past five months. That suggests a dearth of job opportunities for a pool of potential workers that is larger than indicated by the relatively low unemployment rate of 5.3 percent.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It also points to the continuing need to stimulate the economy, create jobs and raise wages. At the bottom of the pay ladder, this could be done through minimum-wage increases; at the middle rungs, it would help to update and enforce labor laws on overtime and benefits. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Of course, many of these and other ideas to foster full employment and rising pay will not be realized without political consensus, something that has long gone missing in Congress. And some things that could be done by the White House or cabinet departments without Congress  remain unfinished or unaddressed. They include new overtime rules, wage and hour protections for home care workers and a requirement that federal contractors support collective bargaining. The longer it takes to achieve these goals, the greater the danger that President Obamaâs term will end and they will be shelved. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At the same time, the Federal Reserve seems determined to begin raising interest rates this year, a move that is generally intended to moderate the economy, even though wage growth, a crucial indicator, has showed no signs of accelerating.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Policy makers went all out to rescue the banks and car companies after the 2008 bust, which allowed many workers to avoid job loss. But policy makers have never directly focused  their will and resources on creating good jobs at good pay. Instead, they seem intent on acting as if the labor market will heal completely on its own. It hasnât and it wonât. </p>
	</div>
		<footer class="entry-footer">
